{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f40cf1bd-c7cf-403a-8958-e7ea4d75cd10","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical transition order:**\n\n| Platform | Sequence |\n|----------|----------|\n| **Foreground** | Created → Activated |\n| **Background** | Deactivated → Stopped (→ Backgrounding on iOS) |\n| **Resume** | Resumed → Activated |\n| **Close** | Deactivated → Stopped → Destroying |\n\n> `Backgrounding` is **iOS/Mac Catalyst only** — use it to save state before the OS may terminate your app. All other events fire on every platform.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d2fb60e1-592b-48f6-848c-b9bd16a7a4f3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to search the codebase since there's no relevant code here. I can answer directly.","outputTokens":423},"id":"800f5207-59c8-415f-a6a6-c9456267e601","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:45:37.117Z","parentId":"f11af977-333c-4cb1-af3d-0956f1ea7762"}
